data.description: We're Black and we're back! Join the Paul Robeson Cultural Center (PRCC) September 9th-13th, 2024 for our Black Welcome Week. There will be programs and events all week long at the PRCC and everyone's invited. What is Black Welcome Week? The Paul Robeson Cultural Center’s Black Welcome Week is a week-long series of programs aimed to introduce Black students to the center, Black faculty and staff, Black student leadership opportunities, and campus resources. With an emphasis on first-year and transfer Black students, our programs are intended to help students get acclimated to campus, empower them, and support them in finding community and increase their sense of belonging.  Students can expect to make new friends, learn how to get involved with the Black Rutgers community, receive good food, get awesome give-aways, and much more! The following programs will take place: Monday, September 9th, Black Graduate Student Mixer, 5:30pm – 7:00pm Tuesday, September 10th, UBC Green Book Presentation (Campus Resources), 8pm – 9:30pm Wednesday, September 11th, Black Wednesday Breakfast, 9am – 11:30am Wednesday, September 11th, Black @ Rutgers Mixer & Panel Discussion, 7:30pm – 9:30pm Friday, September 13th, PRCC Family Reunion Cookout, 3pm – 7pm
data.name: Black Welcome Week 2024

data.description: Join the Black Rutgers student community for an engaging conversation about what it’s really like to be a Black student at Rutgers. This discussion is ideal for first-year and transfer students, but open to all who want to learn more about getting involved, relationships, campus resources, resolving roommate conflict, mental health, and much more! Students will walk away with knowledge about support available on campus and will learn from the lessons shared by student panelists. Additionally, students will get the opportunity to ask panelists questions and will meet other students by engaging in our mixer and ice breakers. Please note this program starts at 7:30pm and light snacks will be served :]
data.name: Black at Rutgers Mixer & Discussion

data.description: We hope you’re having a great start to your semester! We are Anakbayan Rutgers, an on-campus chapter of a mass organization of youth and students fighting to address the struggles of Filipinos – in the Philippines and abroad. We aim to inform others about political issues happening in the Philippines, and engage with members of the local Filipino Community. But most importantly we strive to educate, organize, and mobilize the community, starting right here at Rutgers, to fight towards achieving genuine democracy and freedom. Join us after the Involvement Fair (date tbd), to not only be given a chance to learn more about Anakbayan but also an opportunity for us to become more engaged in the Rutgers community. We hope that you will join us for all the food and fun activities we will be having for this open house, and we look forward to meeting you!

data.description: The goal of this tour is to highlight Israelis and Palestinians who are dedicated to promoting a vision for the future that is founded on values of human rights and peace for all. We hope that by bringing Israelis and Palestinians who are committed to talking and working together, they can be an example for us and help to depolarize our own campus community.     About New Story Leadership Since 2009, NSL has annually brought 10 Israeli and Palestinian delegates to Washington where they lived together with host families, worked together on Capitol Hill, and trained together with DC’s best. They told their stories and advocated for their shared homeland throughout Congress, foreign embassies, the State Department, and faith-based audiences across the Washington DC area. NSL has been proud to elevate the voices of the next generation of leaders committed to working together for justice and peace.    October 7th and its aftermath changed everything. Soon after the war started they reached out to their alumni to check on their safety and ask them what they would like NSL to do. Ten brave NSL alumni -  Muslim, Jewish, and Christian -  from Israel and Palestine, decided to move forward together. After months of research, discussion and an intense week together in Geneva, these young leaders negotiated and drafted the Phoenix Plan. This plan calls for the immediate cessation of hostilities and the freeing of all hostages.  However, it goes much further than that.  The Phoenix Plan sets forth a roadmap for what needs to happen after the fighting stops as agreed upon by young Israelis and Palestinians.  It sets forth a real plan forward for peace, justice, security and self-determination for both Palestinians and Israelis for generations to come.      Yonatan Belik is an Australian-Israeli with a passion for peace. He has participated in initiatives like New Story Leadership and Seeds of Peace where he learned the importance of coexistence and shared his story in front of Congress and Diplomats. He's also dedicated to content creation and travels the world sharing his message of mutual understanding, love, and peace.    Rawan Odeh is a Palestinian-American from Hewara and currently works for monday.com as a Partnerships Manager for social impact. Prior to joining monday.com, Rawan was the Executive Director of New Story Leadership and was a participant of the program back in 2015. Rawan is passionate about sharing her story and her message of a joint Israeli/Palestinian political vision for peace. She has spoken at many J Street events as well as Hillels across the country.
data.name: J Street U at Rutgers Presents: Voices Paving the Path for Peace
data.organizationName: JStreetU of Rutgers University, New Brunswick

data.description: Are you ready to dive into some of today’s most pressing issues and learn how to navigate the complexities of our diverse world? The "Dialogue Through Difference" series is your chance to do just that! In a time when topics like geo-politics conflicts, reproductive rights, affirmative action, and the upcoming election create deep divides, it’s more important than ever to engage in meaningful conversations that bridge our differences. Douglass Residential College is offering a 4-week workshop series designed to equip you with the tools and understanding to build empathy, inclusion, and collaboration within our community. This series isn’t just about talking—it’s about growing, understanding, and building a stronger, more inclusive Douglass community. Don’t miss this opportunity to make a difference. **Students must attend all workshops in order to complete the program for DRC DEI Credit**

data.description: Scarlet Game Jam is a biannual game jam hosted by the Creation of Games Society at Rutgers University. Similar to any other game jam, participants will be given one week(ish) to design and code a game to show off at the end of the jam. At the beginning of each Scarlet Game Jam, we will also be unveiling the (optional) theme to inspire or challenge our participants, which changes with every Scarlet Game Jam, so each year is a new experience! Programmers, musicians, and artists are welcome, but no experience is necessary! Check out our website for more information: (TBD). This time around, the game jam is 2 weeks long to give everyone extra time to work on their games! Feel free to take the whole 2 weeks, one week, or even a single day to work on your game. Join the COGS Discord here! Any announcements about the jam will be blasted here: https://cogs.club/discord Make sure to sign up on our website to ensure free food for the in-person closing ceremony on April 14th. Schedule: TBD
data.name: Scarlet Game Jam Fall 2024
